00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:01.200 align:middle line:84%
had such an intuitive or
intellectual understanding

00:59:01.200 --> 00:59:05.010 align:middle line:84%
of this that they were
able to actually describe

00:59:05.010 --> 00:59:08.210 align:middle line:84%
the idealized
blueprint of creation.

00:59:08.210 --> 00:59:10.420 align:middle line:84%
And that gives us a
standard upon which

00:59:10.420 --> 00:59:13.690 align:middle line:84%
to compare the
idealized blueprint

00:59:13.690 --> 00:59:19.180 align:middle line:84%
with the actual real model
that we're inhabiting.

00:59:19.180 --> 00:59:21.150 align:middle line:84%
As a builder, I know
that there's always

00:59:21.150 --> 00:59:23.560 align:middle line:84%
a deviation between
the blueprints

00:59:23.560 --> 00:59:26.860 align:middle line:84%
as the architect draws them and
the final structure that gets

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:27.360 align:middle line:90%
built.

00:59:27.360 --> 00:59:30.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So that could be the
simple answer to how we ended

00:59:30.480 --> 00:59:31.880 align:middle line:90%
up with those five extra days.

00:59:31.880 --> 00:59:33.570 align:middle line:90%
>>CARLSON: Yes, or could be.

00:59:33.570 --> 00:59:35.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, another
possibility, though,

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:40.910 align:middle line:84%
is that something upset
the balance of things,

00:59:40.910 --> 00:59:44.390 align:middle line:84%
and that's where this extra
